Regression trees: a semi-parametric model

The objective function is:

i=1n(yif(xi))2i=1n(yif(xi))2

But it is infeasible to minimize. The idea is to use the following greedy algorithm:

mins,p[mind1xiR1(s,p)(yid1)2+mind2xiR2(s,p)(yid2)2]mins,p[mind1xiR1(s,p)(yid1)2+mind2xiR2(s,p)(yid2)2]

Where R1={xi,p<s}R1={xi,p<s} and R2={xi,p>s}R2={xi,p>s}

The final predictor has the following form:

f^(x)=m=1MdmI(xRM)f^(x)=m=1MdmI(xRM)

I(xRM)=1I(xRM)=1 if xi,pRMxi,pRM, 00 otherwise. It is easy to shown that:

dm=ave(yi|xiRm)dm=ave(yi|xiRm)


Semi-parametric model:

  • Greedy algorithm to find the best split (sub-optimal solution)
  • Squared error minimization for each node

Issues

  • How many splits
  • How many observations in each node

The size of the tree represents a crucial issue. Consequently we choose the trees adaptively.

Pruning algorithm

Algorithm:

  • Build a large tree (overfitting)
  • Generate n subtree by removing each terminal node
  • Find the out-of-sample MSE of each sub-tree
  • Choose the one with smallest MSPE
  • Continue until convergence

Is it a suboptimal solution?

More precisely:

NmNm the number of observations in each node, |T||T| the number of terminal nodes of a the tree, MSEmMSEm = 1Nmm1(yiym)21Nm1m(yiym)2 yiRmyiRm. The objective function to minimize (cost-complexity criterion) is:

C(T)=m=1|T|NmMSEm(T)+|T|C(T)=m=1|T|NmMSEm(T)+|T|

For each sub-tree TT T0T0 we find the one that minimizes C(T)C(T), where alpha is the usual parameter of a generalized ridge regression.If =0=0 then we get a full tree T0T0. Note that is chosen using the out-of-sample MSE.

Example:

## Overfitting

cc <- tree.control(nobs=nrow(fatalities), mincut=1, minsize=2, 
                    mindev=exp(-30)) ## Look for other values!
full <- tree(fatal ~ beertax + unemp + income  + drinkage, data=fatalities, split='deviance', control=cc) ## Full model


## Pruning back 

set.seed(1322)
## Use cross validation on the full tree
tree.cv <- cv.tree(full) 

## Find the number of nodes with minimum CV deviance: select the smallest

ko <- max(tree.cv$k[min(tree.cv$dev)==tree.cv$dev])

## Prune back 
pruned.tree <- prune.tree(full, k=ko)

plot(pruned.tree)
text(pruned.tree,pretty=FALSE)

Bootstrap

Lets assume that the observations in our sample have been randomly drawn from the true population. The training set is Z=(z1,z2,...,zn)Z=(z1,z2,...,zn) with n observations and zi=(Xi,yi)zi=(Xi,yi).

We can draw with replacement observations from the initial sample and build new samples. It can be shown that the distribution of each of them asyntodically converges to the true distribution under the assumption of randomization of the initial sample.

Consequently we can compute each statistic ^=1BBi=1i^^=1Bi=1Bi^, where BB is the number of bootstrap samples. By construction, under the underlying assumptions:

Var(1Bi=1Bi^)Var(^i)Var(1Bi=1Bi^)Var(^i)

ii , by artificialy increase the number of observations.

Note that the variance cannot go under a given treshold.

Bootstrap is also useful to compute the standard deviation of your statistic:

^2(^)=1B1i=1B(i^b)2^2(^)=1B1i=1B(i^b)2

General Example of Bootstrap:

mu <- 2
n <- 200
set.seed(56)
## Fake data
smpl <- rchisq(n, df = mu)

## CONFIDENCE INTERVAL (based on asymptotics)
xbar <- mean(smpl)
s <- sd(smpl)
c(xbar-1.96*s/sqrt(n), xbar+1.96*s/sqrt(n))
## [1] 1.738785 2.238573
## CONFIDENCE INTERVAL (based on bootstrap)
sim <- 10000
out <- array(0, sim)
for(j in 1:sim) {
  idx <- sample(1:200, 200, replace = TRUE)
  out[j] <- mean(smpl[idx])
}
quantile(out, p=c(0.025, 0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 1.749709 2.247529
## Fake data 2
set.seed(19)
x <- rnorm(100)
y <- 0.3*x + rnorm(100)
plot(x,y)

for (j in 1:sim) {
  idx <- sample(1:100, 100, replace = TRUE)
  out[j] <- cor(y[idx], x[idx])
}



sim <- 100000

out <- array(0, sim)
for (i in 1:sim) {

xbar <- mean(smpl)
out[i] <- sqrt(n)*(xbar-mu)/sqrt(4)
}

h <- 10# Boootstrap h times

mspe <- rep(NA, h) ## null vector to be fill
for (i in 1:h){
## Pick the observations
jj <- sample(1:nrow(wage2), size=nrow(wage2), replace=TRUE)

## Build your new data set
data <- wage2[jj,]

## Now find the MSPE on this new data set!
  ii <- sample(rep(1:k, length= n))
  pr.1 <- rep(NA, n)
  
  for (j in 1:k){
    hold <- (ii == j)
    train <- (ii != j)
    cc <- tree.control(nobs=nrow(data[train,]), mincut=1, minsize=2,      mindev=exp(-30)) ## Look for other values!
    full <- tree(lwage ~ IQ + educ + exper, data=data[train,], split='deviance',     control=cc) 
    tree.cv <- cv.tree(full) 
    ko <- max(tree.cv$k[min(tree.cv$dev)==tree.cv$dev])
    pruned.tree <- prune.tree(full, k=ko)
    pr.1[hold] <- predict(pruned.tree, newdata=data[hold,])

}
## Store the MSPE
mspe[i] <- mean((pr.1-data$lwage)^2)
}

## MSPE - > More accurate (less variance)

## [1] 0.1589331
## SE(MSPE)

sd(mspe)
## [1] 0.007532821

Bagging

Issue with tree

Tree are highly unstable. In fact one error in one of the first split hugely propagates to the subsequent nodes.

How could we make trees more stable?

Example

With simple stumps (1-split trees):

library(tree)
library(rpart)


# bagging on your self


## We use the package rpart, but you may want
## to write your own code using the package tree


set.seed(123)
n <- nrow(wage2)
ii <- sample(n, floor(n/10))

## Build test and training set
dat.te <- wage2[ ii, ]
dat.tr <- wage2[ -ii, ]

# settings to build stumps

stump <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=1,minsplit=0,xval=0)

# how many bootstrapped trees to use
N <- 5
# each column contains the predictions
myps <- matrix(NA, nrow(dat.te), N)
n.tr <- nrow(dat.tr)

set.seed(6)
for(j in 1:N) {
  ii <- sample(n.tr, replace=TRUE)
 tmp <- rpart(lwage ~ IQ + educ + exper , data=dat.tr[ii,], control=stump) 
myps[,j] <- predict(tmp, newdata=dat.te, type='vector')
}
# predictions on the test set
pr.ba <- rowMeans(myps)
mean((dat.te$lwage - pr.ba)^2)
## [1] 0.1506949

With bigger trees:

Out-of-bag MSE

Cross validation may be computationally expensive with bagging.

Short cut: use the observations left behind from each tree as a test set.

Method:

  • Bootstrap B times
  • Each time build a tree on the new sample
  • With each tree make prediction on the out-of-sample observations
  • Take the averaged MSPE among all trees

Example:

control <- rpart.control(cp=0.001,maxdepth=30,minsplit=50,xval=20)

set.seed(6)
N <- 10
n.tr <- nrow(wage2)
set.seed(12)

## store the predictions
myps <- matrix(NA, nrow(wage2), N)

for(j in 1:N) {
  ii <- sample(n.tr, replace=TRUE)
 tmp <- rpart(lwage ~ IQ + educ + exper , data=wage2[ii,], control=control) 
myps[-ii,j] <- predict(tmp, newdata=wage2[-ii,], type='vector')
}

## How many predictions for each tree on average?

(1 - (sum(is.na(myps))/10)/nrow(wage2))
## [1] 0.3680214
## Compute the OOB
pr.ba <- rowMeans(myps, na.rm=TRUE)

##Check if some observations have no predictions
sum(is.na(pr.ba))
## [1] 5
## Store them
kk <- which(is.na(pr.ba))

## remove them
pr.ba <- na.omit(pr.ba)

## Compute the MSPE
mean((wage2$lwage[-kk] - pr.ba)^2)
## [1] 0.1633741

Do you think the OOB can be compared to the cross-validated MSE? Is the size of the bias the same?

Do you think bagging can actually improve the performance of a single tree?


Strong covariates can hugely affect the shape of the trees. With similar trees the variance of your predictors (and predictions) is reduced, and consequently the MSE increases, leading to an ineffective bagging algorithm.

Random Forest is a way to decorrelate trees. Given p covariates the algorithm is:

  • set m between c(1, p) (default: sqrt(p))
  • bootstrap B times (default: 500)
  • For each node of each tree pick randomly m covariates and choose the best split
  • Take the averaged predictions as your estimator
## Example

library(randomForest)
rf <- randomForest(fatal ~ beertax + unemp + milestot + income + youngdrivers , data=fatalities)


## Compare the trainining and test MSE


## Makes prediction on the training set (full set)

plot(rf2, main="Random Forest" ,  ylim= c(0, 300000))
lines(cbind(c(1:500), rf2$test$mse), col="red")
    legend("topright", legend=c("OOB","Training MSE"),        
           cex=1, lwd=c(2.5,2.5),col=c("black","red"))

## Compared to simple bagging

set.seed(6)

myps <- matrix(NA, nrow(fatalities), N)

for(j in 1:N) {

}

Is a random forest only a black box or is there a way to understand the role of covariates?


Measuring variables importance

%IncMSE: Permutation importance

  • Standardized mean difference between the test MSE from predictions of each tree computed before and after permuting a given covariate

IncNodePurity:

  • Total decrease in node impurity (in case of regression MSE) from the splittings of a given variable, averaged over all trees, no matter the position of the node where the split has occurred.
## Analyzing manualy each tree of a forest

a1 <- getTree(rf, k = 1, labelVar = TRUE)
## Display a1 and see your self...

## Short cut to visualize the importance

## Put in order variables for importance

## Take the names and the values of the variables

values <- rf$importance[ko]
### General settings (try your self....)
par(las=2, mar=c(5,6,6,5))

##Make your plot
barplot(values, names.arg= names ,horiz=TRUE, main="Variables importance", col="purple", cex.names=1)

## Bagging

## Note we use parallel execution in this case


library(foreach)
library(rpart)
## Write your function for bagging

bagging<-function(X, y, x.te = NULL, y.te = NULL, control= rpart.control(minsplit = 20, minbucket = round(minsplit/3)),  trees=100)
{

## If no data test provided it reports the oob MSE
if (is.null(x.te)){    
OOB<-foreach(m=1:trees,.combine=cbind) %dopar% {

## Bootstrap and build each tree
ii <- sample(1:length(y), replace=TRUE)
data <- cbind(y, X)
tmp <- rpart(y[ii] ~. , data=data[ii,]) ## Default settings for tree, change on your self it!
vec <- rep(NA, length(y))

## Make your predictions

vec[-ii] <- predict(tmp, newdata=data[-ii,], type='vector')
vec
}

## Store the predictions
pred <- rowMeans(OOB, na.rm=TRUE)

## Check for missing values
kk <- which(is.na(pred))
pred <- na.omit(pred)

  ## Compute the MSE OOB
  if (length(kk)==0){ mean((y - pred)^2) } else { mean((y[-kk] - pred)^2) }

}  else {   
  
  ## Report predictions on the test set if data test is provided
     
predictions <- foreach(m=1:trees,.combine=cbind) %dopar% {

ii <- sample(1:length(y), replace=TRUE)
data <- cbind(y, X)
data.te <- cbind(y.te, x.te)

## Give the same name to the data test
names(data.te) <- append("y", colnames(X))
tmp <- rpart(y[ii] ~. , data=data[ii,]) 
predict(tmp, newdata=data.te, type='vector')
}
rowMeans(predictions)
}
  

}

Classification trees

Discussion:

How could we apply similar algorithms also to classification problems?


Remember from regression trees:

  • Semi parametric model
  • Greedy algorithm which maximize the purity of regions

Idea:

  • Split data in regions that are clearly dominated from a certain class using still a greedy algorithm

What is the difference from K-NN? Could it suffers for curse of dimensionality?

We define p^k,m=total ykRmtotal yRmp^k,m=total ykRmtotal yRm the estimated probability for the observation of being of class k in a given node RmRm.

The most homogenous tree would be the one with p^k,m=p^j,n=1 k,mj,np^k,m=p^j,n=1 k,mj,n, each node with only one class. But of course this plit would lead to overfit.

So we want to set some minimum tresholds:

  • Nodes with a minimum number of observations (no trivial splits of only few or one observations)
  • Treshold on the gain in terms of deviance

Measure of purity:

  • Gini Index
  • Deviance

Gini Index:

Qg=kjipjpi=kj=1pj(1pj)Qg=jikpjpi=j=1kpj(1pj)

Deviance:

Dg=2kj=1pjln(pj)Dg=2j=1kpjln(pj)

The two are extremelly similar in practice and we will use the Gini Index.

For each split the algorithm finds:

argminXj,anlQ({Xj<a}N)+nrQ({Xj>a}N)argminXj,anlQ({Xj<a}N)+nrQ({Xj>a}N)

Where nlnl and nrnr are the number of observations in the left and right nodes of a subtree with in total NN observations.

De facto, for each split the greedy algorithm minimizes the sum of the impurity multiplied by the size of the new nodes (in order to avoid trivial splits).

Ensamble techniques

The same techniques used for regression applies to classification, with the only difference that now we have a different measure of purity.

Bagging and Random Forest are commonly used to reduce the variance of the predictor.

Examples:

Exercise

We want to distinguish spam emails from non-spam emails. To do so, we have at disposal a data set with 4601 observations, 57 covariates and the dependent variable equal to one for spam email and zero otherwise.

Explore the data set, provides some statistics regarding the variables and try to understand the main reasoning. Which regression would you use?

  • Split data in a test and training set
  • Build a bagging algorithm to make predictions on the test set
  • Repeat the process with a random forest, compute the test error rate and the OOB error rate

Challenges:

  • Focus your attention on specificity and sensitivity. Plot a ROC curve and try to maximizes both, choosing a good treshold.
  • Baggig by hand: write a function to do bagging with a classification problem. Use parallel execution. (Hint: use the function provided in the solution of the exercise with regression)
library(rpart)

spambase <- read.table("./data/spambase.txt")
spambase$spam <- as.factor(spambase$spam)
set.seed(1)
ii <- sample(1:dim(spambase)[1], replace=FALSE, size= floor(dim(spambase)[1]/5))
data.tr <- spambase[-ii,]
data.te <- spambase[ii,]

x.tr <- data.tr[,-58]
y.tr <- data.tr[,58]
x.te <- data.te[,-58]
y.te <- data.te[,58]

stump <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=1,minsplit=0,xval=0)

set.seed(6)
N <- 100 ## We use 100 trees!
set.seed(12)
myps <- matrix(NA, nrow(data.te), N)

for(j in 1:N) {
  ii <- sample(nrow(data.tr), replace=TRUE)
 tmp <- rpart(as.factor(y.tr) ~., data=x.tr[ii,], control=stump) 
myps[,j] <- as.numeric(as.character(predict(tmp, newdata=x.te, type='class'))) ##!!
}

## Take the majority vote

pr.ba <- rowMeans(myps, na.rm=TRUE)

## For number lower then 0.5 set 0, 1 otherwis

pr.ba[pr.ba<0.5] <- 0
pr.ba[pr.ba>=0.5] <- 1
mean(y.te != pr.ba)
## [1] 0.3945652

sensitivity <- spec.1 <- rep(NA, length=length(seq(0,1, by = 0.01)))
k <- 1

## Look at the test set
y <- as.numeric(as.character(y.te)) # Use this trick to be able to make numeric operation with factors
for (i in seq(0,1, by = 0.01)){   
pred <-as.numeric(as.character(rf$test$votes[,2])) ## Note I pick votes!! 
pred[pred>=i] <- 1
pred[pred<i] <- 0


# Specificity 

 sensitivity[k]  <-  sum( (y == 0) & (pred == 0) ) / sum( y == 0)
 spec.1[k] <- (1 - sum( (y == 1) & (pred == 1) ) / sum( y == 1))
  k <- k + 1
  }

plot(cbind(spec.1, sensitivity), type="n", main="ROC", xlab="Specificity of 1", ylab="Sensitivity")
lines(cbind(spec.1, sensitivity), col="red", lwd=2)

## First solution: pick the minimum distance from the upper-left corner

## Simply use pitagora's theorem

squared.distances <- (1-sensitivity)^2 + spec.1^2

## Pick the treshold with the minimum distance

tr <- seq(0,1, by = 0.01)[which.min(squared.distances)]


## Make your predictions and look at the new confusion matrix
pred <-as.numeric(as.character(rf$test$votes[,2])) ## Note I pick votes!! 
pred[pred>=tr] <- 1
pred[pred<tr] <- 0

confusion <- table(pred, y.te)
class.error <- append(1 - sum( (y.te == 0) & (pred == 0) ) / sum( y.te == 0), 
1 - sum( (y.te == 1) & (pred == 1) ) / sum( y.te == 1))

## Challenge 2 : bagging by hand: many solutions are admitted

library(foreach)
library(rpart)
bagging_class <-function(X, y, x.te = NULL, y.te = NULL,  trees=100)
{

## If no data test provided it reports the oob error rate
if (is.null(x.te)){    
OOB<-foreach(m=1:trees,.combine=cbind) %dopar% {

## Bootstrap and build each tree
ii <- sample(1:length(y), replace=TRUE)
data <- cbind(y, X)
data$y <- as.factor(data$y)
tmp <- rpart(y[ii] ~. , data=data[ii,]) 
vec <- rep(NA, length(y))

## Make your predictions

vec[-ii] <- as.numeric(as.character(predict(tmp, newdata=data[-ii,], type="class")))
vec
}

## Take the probability
pred <- rowMeans(OOB, na.rm=TRUE)



## Check for missing values
kk <- which(is.na(pred))
pred <- na.omit(pred)


## Use 0.5 treshold

pred[pred >=0.5] <- 1
pred[pred< 0.5] <-0 
  ## Compute the error rate
  if (length(kk)==0){ mean((y != pred)) } else { mean((y[-kk] != pred)) }

}  else {   
  
  ## Report predictions on the test set if data test is provided
     
predictions <- foreach(m=1:trees,.combine=cbind) %dopar% {

ii <- sample(1:length(y), replace=TRUE)
data <- cbind(y, X)
data.te <- cbind(y.te, x.te)

## Give the same name to the data test
names(data.te) <- append("y", colnames(X))
data$y <- as.factor(data$y)
tmp <- rpart(y[ii] ~. , data=data[ii,]) 
predict(tmp, newdata=data.te, type='class')
}
## Report probabilities
rowMeans(predictions)
}
  

}

Boosting

With boosting we will now move away from the case of 0/1 loss function and we will introduce more complex decision boundaries based on different weights given to observations.

Theoretical Framework

The loss funcion we have used until now was

1Ni=1nI(yig(Xi))1Ni=1nI(yig(Xi))

But now we want to weight errors according to the distance between the predicted posterior probability and the true class of the observation.

A general definition for a predictor may be:

g(xi,)=j=1kjf(xi,j)g(xi,)=j=1kjf(xi,j)

With jj = (jj, jj) . For a linear regression function f(xi,j)=xj,if(xi,j)=xj,i, while in other cases such as basis expansion models the function can be much more complex. Given (yi,f(xi,j))(yi,f(xi,j)) a certain loss function we would like to solve:

=argmin,i=1n(yi,j=1kjf(xi,j))=argmin,i=1n(yi,j=1kjf(xi,j))

Unfortunately this is a very complex problem. There are many short-cuts to avoid this impossible computation. An approximation can be done by fixing a certain function ff and use a stepwise algorithm. In this case the problem becomes:

=argmin,i=1n(yi,fj1(xi)+jf(xi,j))=argmin,i=1n(yi,fj1(xi)+jf(xi,j))

where fj=fj1(xi)+jf(xi,j)fj=fj1(xi)+jf(xi,j).

Adaboost is a weak learner algorithm very similar to forward stagewise which uses a particular loss function.

We first define a new loss:

L(y,g(x))=eyg(x)L(y,g(x))=eyg(x)

What is the intuition?

With this new function the basis expansion becomes:

=argmin,Gi=1nexp(yi(fj1(xi)+G(xi))=argmin,Gi=1nexp(yi(fj1(xi)+G(xi))

At each step mm the classifier GmGm and are computed. This can be written as

=argmin,Gi=1nw(m)iexp(yiG(xi))=argmin,Gi=1nwi(m)exp(yiG(xi))

where w(m)i=exp(yif(xi)m1)wi(m)=exp(yif(xi)m1). Note that the weights do not depends on the parameter and , in this case, the problem is solvable.

For any >0>0 the solution can be written as (HFT, pag. 343)

G(x)=argminGi=1nw(m)iI(yig(Xi))G(x)=argminGi=1nwi(m)I(yig(Xi))

And plugging the solution in the f.o.c. (we are dealing each time with a convex problem)

=12log1errmerrm=12log1errmerrm

Where errmerrm is the minimized weighted error rate

ni=1w(m)iI(yig(Xi))ni=1w(m)ii=1nwi(m)I(yig(Xi))i=1nwi(m)

In practice


  1. Initialize the observations with same weights (1N1N)


  1. from m in 1:M


    • fit G(x)mG(x)m using the actual weights
    • compute errm=ni=1w(m)iI(yig(Xi))ni=1w(m)ierrm=i=1nwi(m)I(yig(Xi))i=1nwi(m)
    • compute m=log1errmerrmm=log1errmerrm
    • set wi,m+1:=wi,mexp(mI(yig(Xi)))wi,m+1:=wi,mexp(mI(yig(Xi)))


  1. Predictor: G(x)m=sign[Mm=1mGm(x)]G(x)m=sign[m=1MmGm(x)]

Note that G(x)G(x) is generally a tree, but you can use the same algorithm with other functions.

What are we estimating?

The population solution of a classification problem with exponential loss is:

f(x)=argminf(x)EY|X[exp(Yf(x))]f(x)=argminf(x)EY|X[exp(Yf(x))]

It is trivial to show in a two-class scenario that this number is equal to: 12logP(Y=1|X)P(Y1|X)12logP(Y=1|X)P(Y1|X)

The same result applies to other losses such as the deviance. It means that asyntadically different losses may have similar results. But with approximations

Issues:

  • How many interations?
  • What is the best size of the tree?

Note:

  • The deepest the tree, the higher the level of interactions between variables. If the real f(x)f(x) is characterized by many interations boosting may work only with many-nodes trees, while if there are no interetions stumps may perform extremelly well.

  • The algorithm does not converge by definition and the evolution of the error can be more unstable compared to other algorithms.

Example

library(adabag)
library(rpart)

heart_train <- read.table("./data/heart_train.txt")
heart_test <- read.table("./data/heart_test_with_y.txt")
## heart data test and training set

## With stumps

stump <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=1,minsplit=0,xval=0)
heart_train$chd <- as.factor(heart_train$chd)
heart_test$chd <- as.factor(heart_test$chd)

heart_train <- na.omit(heart_train)
set.seed(1)
bb <- boosting(chd~., data=heart_train, boos = FALSE, mfinal = 100, coeflearn = 'Breiman', control=stump)


## Be careful to the test set...


err_te <- errorevol(bb, newdata=heart_test)


plot(err_te, lwd=2)

## Change the tree
 
contr <- rpart.control(cp=exp(-50),maxdepth=30,minsplit=0)


## Comparing with a random forest

rr <- randomForest(heart_train$chd~., data=heart_train[,-11], tree=100, xtest=heart_test[,-c(1,11)], ytest = heart_test[,11])

plot(cbind(c(1:100), err_te$error), main= "Ensambles on Heart Test set", type="n", ylim=c(0.05, 0.50), xlab="trees", ylab="Test Error Rate")
lines(cbind(c(1:100), rr$test$err.rate[c(1:100),1]), col="blue", lwd=2)
lines(cbind(c(1:100), err_te$error), col="red", lwd=2)

 legend("topright", legend=c("Boosting","Random Forest"), cex=0.8, lwd=c(2.5,2.5),col=c("red","blue"))

Exercise

During this exercise we will generate data to understand the performance of Adabag in several circumstances.

First:

  • Generate 10 variables uniformly distributed between -1 and 1 of length 300.
  • Define yV1+3V2+2yV1+3V2+2 and add a white noise. Generate a dependent variable equal to one for positive y, 0 otherwise.
  • Use 250 variables as your training set and 50 as a test set.
  • Build a boosting model using stumps with all the variables in X.
  • Now repeat the process with large trees
  • Report the Test Error Rate of the two models

Then:

  • Set yV1V2V3+3V2+2V3+V102V4V9+exp(V5)+sin(V1)yV1V2V3+3V2+2V3+V102V4V9+exp(V5)+sin(V1)
  • Is boosting a suitable algorithm using stumps?
  • Can you explain which kind of trees would you choose?

Solution

set.seed(123)
X <- matrix(0, 300, 10)
for (i in 1:10){
  X[,i] <- runif(300,-1,1)
}


y <- X[,1] + 3*X[,2] + rnorm(300)
y <- ifelse(y>=0, 1, 0)

set.seed(123)
ii <- sample(1:nrow(X), replace=FALSE, size=50)
stump <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=1,minsplit=0,xval=0)
data <- as.data.frame(cbind(y,X))
data$y <- as.factor(data$y)

data.test <- data[ii,]
data.train <- data[-ii,]

set.seed(123)
bb <- boosting(y~., data=data.train, boos = FALSE, mfinal = 100, coeflearn = 'Freund', control=stump)

err_te <- errorevol(bb, newdata=data.test)

plot(err_te)

##Training 

mean(bb$class != data.train$y)
## [1] 0.028
## Test

err_te$error[which.min(err_te$error)]
## [1] 0.1
## Change control tree

bigger <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=10,minsplit=1,xval=0)


bb2 <- boosting(y~., data=data.train, boos = FALSE, mfinal = 100, coeflearn = 'Freund', control=bigger)

## Training 

mean(bb2$class != data.train$y)
## [1] 0
## Test....


predict(bb2, newdata=data.test)$error 
## [1] 0.16
### Second part of the exercise

y <- X[,1]*X[,2]*X[,3] + 3*X[,2] + 2*X[,3] + X[,10]^2* X[,4]*X[,9] + exp(X[,5]) + sin(X[,1]) + rnorm(300)
y <- ifelse(y>=0, 1, 0)

## Repeat everything...


ii <- sample(1:nrow(X), replace=FALSE, size=50)
stump <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=1,minsplit=0,xval=0)
data <- as.data.frame(cbind(y,X))
data$y <- as.factor(data$y)

data.test <- data[ii,]
data.train <- data[-ii,]

set.seed(123)
bb <- boosting(y~., data=data.train, boos = FALSE, mfinal = 100, coeflearn = 'Freund', control=stump)
err_te <- errorevol(bb, newdata=data.test)

## Change control tree
bigger <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=2,minsplit=1,xval=0)

bb2 <- boosting(y~., data=data.train, boos = FALSE, mfinal = 100, coeflearn = 'Freund', control=bigger)

## See predict with boosting, larger trees capture the interactions...

##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,] 0.12  0.1

Republicans VS Democrats: same game?

Open the HouseVotes84 Data. The dataset reports the 1984 United Stated Congressional Voting Records. For each deputy we know what she voted in the past 16 different votations.

First

We want to distinguish Republicans from Democrats.

  • Explore the dataset, provide some initial statistics. Clean the data.
  • Find the best classification model among the ones we used using a suitable measure of error.

Then

  • Assume that votation comes one after the other from the first to the 16th and they have the same importance to deputies. Find a model to predict the behaviour of deputies for the 16th votation.

Challenge:

  • Find a model to predict the 17th votation (many possible answers allowed).
## Solution

data(HouseVotes84, package="mlbench")
## Huge reduction of observations..... Tru to interpolate yourself
HouseVotes <- na.omit(HouseVotes84)

### We use boosting to predict Republicans Vs Democrats

stump <- rpart.control(cp=-1,maxdepth=1,minsplit=0,xval=0)
set.seed(2)
ii <- sample(1:nrow(HouseVotes), replace=TRUE, size = floor(nrow(HouseVotes)/3))
data.test <- HouseVotes[ii,]
data.train <- HouseVotes[-ii,]
library(adabag)
set.seed(123)
bb <- boosting(Class ~., data=data.train, boos = FALSE, mfinal = 100, coeflearn = 'Freund', control=stump)
err_te <- predict(bb, newdata=data.test)
## Confusion matrix
